'''Paul Grundy MD, MPH, FACOEM, FACPM''', known as the "Godfather" of the [[Medical home|Patient Centered Medical Home]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Doctor's Digest: Primary Care and the Medical Home|url=http://elizabethgardner.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/Doctors-Digest-Primary-Care-and-the-Medical-Home-May-June-2009.pdf}}</ref> member of the [[Institute of Medicine]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Institute of Medicine|url=http://www.iom.edu/Global/News%20Announcements/2012-New-Members.aspx}}</ref> and recipient of the 2012 [[National Committee for Quality Assurance]](NCQA) Quality Award,<ref>{{cite web|title=NCQA|url=http://www.ncqa.org/Sponsorship/ConferenceSponsorshipPackage/2012HealthQualityAwardsDinner.aspx}}</ref> is [[IBM|IBM's]]  Global Director of [[Healthcare]] Transformation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paul Grundy, Human Resource Director|url=http://www.ibm.com/solutions/genographic/us/en/landing/F039360P78724G00.html|work=The Genographic Project|accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Healthcare reform relies on IT and prevention|url=https://www-304.ibm.com/businesscenter/cpe/html0/166467.html|work=IBM Business Center|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref>

In this role, Dr. Grundy develops and executes strategies that support IBM’s healthcare-industry transformation initiatives. Part of his work is directed towards shifting healthcare delivery around the world towards consumer-focused, primary-care based systems through the adoption of new philosophies,<ref>{{cite news|title=Study Shows ‘Invisible’ Burden of Family Doctors|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/29/business/29doctor.html?scp=3&sq=%22paul%20Grundy%22&st=cse|publisher=''The New York Times'' | first=Steve|last=Lohr|date=28 April 2010}}</ref> primary-care pilot programs<ref>{{cite news|title=UnitedHealth and I.B.M. Test Health Care Plan|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/07/business/07medhome.html?_r=2&scp=1&sq=%22paul%20Grundy%22&st=cse|publisher=''The New York Times'' | first=Reed | last=Abelson | date=7 February 2009}}</ref>
,new incentives systems,<ref>{{cite news|title=Trying to Save by Increasing Doctors' Fees|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/21/business/21medhome.html?scp=7&sq=%22paul%20Grundy%22&st=cse|publisher=''The New York Times'' | first=Milt | last=Freudenheim | date=21 July 2008}}</ref> and the information technology required to implement such change. He is one of only 38 IBMers and the only physician selected into IBM’s senior 
industry leadership forum know as the IBM Industry Academy.<ref>{{cite web|title=IBM Industry Academy| url=https://www.ecri.org/Documents/Conferences/2012_TA_Conf/P_Grundy_bio.pdf}}</ref> 

Dr. Grundy is also the Founding President<ref>{{cite web|title=Patient-Centered Primary Care Collaborative|url=http://www.pcpcc.net/profile/paul-grundy}}</ref> of the [http://www.pcpcc.net Patient Centered Primary Care Collaborative] and is an Adjunct Professor, [[University of Utah School of Medicine]], Department of [[Family Medicine|Family]] and [[Preventive Medicine]]. 

An active social entrepreneur and speaker<ref>{{cite web|title=TEDxMaastricht| url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=npc0PLcYyxM}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dr.GrundyPresentations| url=http://www.slideshare.net/DrGrundy}}</ref> on global healthcare transformation, Dr. Grundy is driving comprehensive, linked, and integrated healthcare and the concept of the [[Medical home|Patient Centered Medical Home]]. His work has been reported widely in the New York Times, BusinessWeek, Forbes<ref>{{cite news|title=IBM Unleashes "Primary Care Spring"|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/davechase/2012/08/27/primary-care-spring-unleashed-by-ibm/|publisher=''Forbes''}}</ref>, the Economist<ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist's Healthcare in Asia 2013|url=https://www-950.ibm.com/events/wwe/grp/grp033.nsf/v16_speakers?openform&seminar=B9EKMEES&locale=en_ZZ&S_TACT=103FR01M}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Economist's Healthcare in Asia 2013|url=http://www.economistconferences.asia/video/healthcare-asia-2013-summit/1504|publisher=Video}}</ref>, the Huffington Post<ref>{{cite news|title=The Huffington Post: Dr. Paul Grundy|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/dr-paul-grundy/}}</ref>, New England Journal of Medicine and newspapers, radio and television around the country. 

